\name{QC_resample}
\alias{QC_resample}
%- Also NEED an '\alias' for EACH other topic documented here.
\title{
Quality control with count resampling for batch correction evaluation
}
\description{
%%  ~~ A concise (1-5 lines) description of what the function does. ~~
Evaluates batch correction quality by resampling raw RNA-seq count data using a statistical model (multinomial or negative binomial), normalising and batch-correcting the resampled data, and computing quality metrics on diluted series of corrected data.
}
\usage{
QC_resample(CountData, coldata = NULL, batches, groups,
            metrics = c("F-score", "Davies-Bouldin", "kNN", "mindist",
                        "kldist", "skewdiv"),
            iters = 100,
            corrMethod = "ComBat",
            mod = NULL,
            Ctrl_sample,
            y = NULL,
            levels = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1),
            dilute_samples = FALSE,
            design = NULL,
            normalization = "deseq",
            parallel = TRUE,
            nCores = 16,
            usePCA = FALSE,
            nPCs = 50,
            var.model = "multinom")
}
%- maybe also 'usage' for other objects documented here.
\arguments{
  \item{CountData}{
%%     ~~Describe \code{x} here~~
A raw RNA-seq count matrix with rows as genes and columns as samples.
}

  \item{coldata}{
An optional data frame with columns \code{batch} and \code{group}. If NULL, it is constructed from \code{batches} and \code{groups}.
}

  \item{batches}{
A vector of batch labels for each sample.
}

  \item{groups}{
A vector of biological group labels for each sample.
}

  \item{metrics}{
A character vector of metric names to compute. Default includes \code{"F-score"}, \code{"Davies-Bouldin"}, \code{"kNN"}, \code{"mindist"}, \code{"kldist"} and \code{"skewdiv"}.
}

  \item{iters}{
The number of resampling iterations. Default is 100.
}

  \item{corrMethod}{
String specifying the batch correction method (\code{"ComBat"}, \code{"limma"} or \code{"harmony"}). Default is \code{"ComBat"}.
}

  \item{mod}{
An optional model matrix to pass to ComBat. If NULL, one is constructed from \code{groups}.
}

  \item{Ctrl_sample}{
String specifying the reference (control) sample type for DESeq2 normalisation.
}

  \item{y}{
Optional response variable for metrics that require it.
}

  \item{levels}{
A numeric vector of batch correction dilution levels. Default is \code{seq(0, 1, by = 0.1)}.
}

  \item{dilute_samples}{
Logical. Whether to use sample-based dilution (\code{\link{ADS_A}}) instead of gene-level dilution. Default is FALSE.
}

  \item{design}{
An optional formula for the DESeq2 or negative binomial model. If NULL, a default formula is used.
}

  \item{normalization}{
String specifying the normalisation method: \code{"deseq"} (default) or \code{"scuttle"}.
}

  \item{parallel}{
Logical. Whether to run iterations in parallel. Default is TRUE.
}

  \item{nCores}{
The number of CPU cores to use for parallel computation. Default is 16.
}

  \item{usePCA}{
Logical. Whether to reduce dimensionality with PCA before computing distance-based metrics. Default is FALSE.
}

  \item{nPCs}{
The number of principal components to use when \code{usePCA = TRUE}. Default is 50.
}

  \item{var.model}{
String specifying the count resampling model: \code{"multinom"} (Dirichlet-multinomial, default) or \code{"nbinom"} (negative binomial via DESeq2).
}

}
\details{
%%  ~~ If necessary, more details than the description above ~~
In each iteration, new count data are generated by resampling from the observed counts using the specified model. The resampled data are normalised and batch-corrected, and quality metrics are computed on a diluted series of the corrected data (from 0\% to 100\% correction). The results can be used to assess metric sensitivity and batch correction quality.
}
\value{
%%  ~Describe the value returned
A list of length \code{iters}, where each element is a list with components:
\item{bio}{A list of metric values for the biological group separation at each dilution level.}
\item{batch}{A list of metric values for the batch separation at each dilution level.}
\item{ratio}{A list of bio/batch metric ratios at each dilution level.}
%% ...
}
